<font color="#FF0000">YESTERDAYSBATTLE</font><br>
<tt>Sat Nov 22 10:55:01 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
GGGGOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOODDDD MOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOORNNG VIIIETNAM!!!!<br><br>
Gosh, I love the smell of Napalm in the Morning!<br><br>
Looks like there was a battle here last night and no one called for GUNS UP!<br><br>
30 years ago, yesterday was one of the worst day in Nam, I was at the bank yesterday with my daughter when I asked her what day it was and she told me. She saw the look in my eyes and asked, why? Oh, I said, just that a lot of guys got killed and wounded on this day 30 years ago. <br><br>
Yesterdays battle 30 years ago is one of the main points in my diary, from then on everything changed. 47 of us went in 12 of us walked out. From then on the rest of Nam was vague, dream like. <br>
Late that evening the gooks kept yelling at us, Cam-kook, cam-kook Mahreene, mahreene, tonight you die, mahreene, mahreene tonight you die.&quot;  A short time later they assaulted, but they never made it across the first rice paddy dike. <br><br>
Two did, one threw a grenade. Doc Mac dragged me back and tagged me to be medivacked. My legs were paralyzed, all I could do was crawl, Guys hurting all over the place, we only had one m-60 firing, so Aggie my a-gunner, teamed up with Jones, and Marty. I gave someone my .45. They fixed bayonets and broke out the gas and gas masks. <br><br>
But the assault never came, a couple hours later, four big chinook helicopters came in with Foxtrot 2/7. They were, skuzzy, dirty, angry Marines. Jumped out typical John Wayne style, assaulting the two company’s of entrenched NVA, with their reinforced sapper platoon. <br>
The Marines had been told that the enemy had a platoon of Marines pinned down in the finger lake area of Arizona territory. <br><br>
They came in with the penned up anger of months of fighting an elusive enemy. But the enemy had stayed too long, they wanted to finish of the remains of 1st platoon, India Company 3 Bn 7th Marines, right there at the bend in the river. <br><br>
But they had not counted on Colonel Bernard in the rear, who said, to the Captain of Foxtrot, “Go, get them,.” and they did. <br><br>
Gosh I could have kissed and pinned medals on everyone one of those Marines that evening, They brought out Lucero, Keenan, Cox and another Marine who had been captured or who had played dead at the foot of the entrenched enemy while we had fired back and forth that day. I have never forgotten the look on those liberated Marines eyes. <br><br>
I guess its fitting that all of you fought yesterdays battle, In Nam we had Artillery, Air Force and even Army (yep!) Army choppers come in sprayed the area for us several times. BaBa Perry got his name that day when he shot a rocket at a hooch to mark it for the Army chopper to drop his rockets into it. The back blast blew out Perrys ear drums, all he could say after the dust and dirt settled was, baa, baaa,  <br><br>
Great battle guys and Anne. <br>
Cook<br>

